<div class="rellink boilerplate seealso">See also: <a href="/wiki/Jewish_services" title="Jewish services">Jewish services</a></div>
<p>Listed below are some <a href="/wiki/Hebrew_language" title="Hebrew language">Hebrew</a> <a href="/wiki/Jewish_services" title="Jewish services">prayers</a> and <a href="/wiki/Berakhah" title="Berakhah">blessings</a> that are part of <a href="/wiki/Judaism" title="Judaism">Judaism</a> that are recited by many <a href="/wiki/Jew" title="Jew">Jews</a>. This article addresses Jewish liturgical blessings, which generally begin with the formula:</p>
<div style="direction: rtl; unicode-bidi: embed;" lang="he" xml:lang="he"><span style="font-size:125%; font-family:&quot;SBL Hebrew&quot;, David, Narkisim, &quot;Microsoft Sans Serif&quot;, &quot;Times New Roman&quot;" dir="rtl">ברוך אתה <a href="/wiki/Tetragrammaton" title="Tetragrammaton">ה'</a> <a href="/wiki/Elohim" title="Elohim">א‑לוהינו</a> מלך העולם...‏</span></div>
<p><a href="/wiki/Transliteration" title="Transliteration">Transliteration</a>: <i>Barukh ata Adonai Eloheinu melekh ha‑olam...</i></p>
<p><a href="/wiki/Translation" title="Translation">Translation</a>: "Blessed are You, L<small>ORD</small>, our God, King of the universe..."</p>
<table id="toc" class="toc" summary="Contents">
